WEBVTT

00:03.503 --> 00:04.004
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

00:04.004 --> 00:05.172
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

00:05.172 --> 00:07.007
<i>‐ Over the last few years,</i>

00:07.007 --> 00:08.509
<i>99 groups of bladesmiths</i>

00:08.509 --> 00:09.927
<i>from around the country</i>
<i>and the world</i>

00:09.927 --> 00:11.303
<i>have entered The Forge...</i>

00:11.303 --> 00:12.846
‐ Rah!

00:12.846 --> 00:14.139
<i>‐ In hopes of earning</i>
<i>the coveted title</i>

00:14.139 --> 00:15.682
<i>of "Forged in Fire" Champion.</i>

00:15.682 --> 00:17.100
‐ Can you believe it?

00:17.100 --> 00:19.061
‐ This is like, the proudest
moment of my entire life.

00:19.061 --> 00:22.189
<i>‐ Tonight, our landmark</i>
<i>100th competition.</i>

00:22.189 --> 00:23.690
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

00:23.690 --> 00:26.652
<i>Four bladesmiths face</i>
<i>familiar feats</i>

00:26.652 --> 00:28.237
<i>with surprising challenges.</i>

00:28.237 --> 00:29.571
<i>♪ ♪</i>

00:29.571 --> 00:32.074
As with our previous
99 episodes,

00:32.074 --> 00:34.952
<i>you just never know</i>
<i>what's gonna happen</i>

00:34.952 --> 00:36.328
<i>here in The Forge.</i>

00:36.328 --> 00:37.829
<i>Which bladesmith</i>
<i>will triumph</i>

00:37.829 --> 00:39.248
<i>on this momentous occasion...</i>

00:39.248 --> 00:41.291
Whoa, watch your face.

00:41.291 --> 00:43.585
<i>And walk away with ten grand</i>

00:43.585 --> 00:46.088
<i>as the latest</i>
<i>"Forged in Fire" Champion?</i>

00:46.088 --> 00:47.548
<i>♪ ♪</i>

00:47.548 --> 00:50.592
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

00:50.592 --> 00:56.807
<i>♪ ♪</i>

00:56.807 --> 00:58.558
<i>‐ My name's Mickey Thompson.</i>

00:58.558 --> 01:00.269
I'm 48 years old.

01:00.269 --> 01:01.979
<i>I've been making blades</i>
<i>for over 15 years,</i>

01:01.979 --> 01:03.605
<i>and I love every minute of it.</i>

01:03.605 --> 01:05.649
The first couple knives
I made were out of files,

01:05.649 --> 01:07.401
<i>and my taxidermist liked them,</i>

01:07.401 --> 01:09.736
and I was hooked after that.

01:09.736 --> 01:10.862
<i>♪ ♪</i>

01:10.862 --> 01:12.239
‐ My name is Cullen Erbacher.

01:12.239 --> 01:13.615
I'm 44 years old.

01:13.615 --> 01:14.992
<i>I'm here to challenge myself,</i>

01:14.992 --> 01:16.910
<i>so whatever they throw at us,</i>

01:16.910 --> 01:18.203
<i>I'm excited about it.</i>

01:18.203 --> 01:19.997
Every other form of art
I ever tried,

01:19.997 --> 01:21.748
I'm not very good at,
and it turns out

01:21.748 --> 01:24.751
that I can hit metal that's hot
and make something.

01:24.751 --> 01:26.753
<i>[rock music]</i>

01:26.753 --> 01:28.922
<i>‐ My name is Robert Guest.</i>
<i>I'm 28 years old.</i>

01:28.922 --> 01:32.050
I joined the Army in 2012.

01:32.050 --> 01:34.303
<i>It's hard to find time</i>
<i>to care for yourself,</i>

01:34.303 --> 01:36.054
<i>and I found that that's what</i>
<i>bladesmithing does for me.</i>

01:36.054 --> 01:37.931
<i>It provides me an outlet</i>
<i>for self‐care.</i>

01:37.931 --> 01:39.391
<i>I think bladesmithing</i>
<i>definitely can be something</i>

01:39.391 --> 01:41.018
<i>that‐‐that's helpful</i>
<i>for veterans.</i>

01:41.018 --> 01:42.853
It forces you to focus,
and it keeps your mind

01:42.853 --> 01:44.771
off of some
of the negative things

01:44.771 --> 01:45.939
that you've had to see or do.

01:45.939 --> 01:47.024
<i>♪ ♪</i>

01:47.024 --> 01:48.275
<i>‐ My name is Sam Hallett.</i>

01:48.275 --> 01:49.651
<i>I'm 26 years old.</i>

01:49.651 --> 01:51.111
I primarily make swords.

01:51.111 --> 01:53.322
<i>Most of the stuff I make</i>
<i>is from history.</i>

01:53.322 --> 01:56.867
<i>I just enjoy</i>
<i>the complex aspect of them.</i>

01:56.867 --> 01:59.411
Also, it's just fun
to have big swords.

01:59.411 --> 02:02.289
‐ Bladesmiths,
welcome to The Forge.

02:02.289 --> 02:03.790
<i>♪ ♪</i>

02:03.790 --> 02:05.667
You're here to engage
in three timed rounds

02:05.667 --> 02:07.127
of edged weapon‐making
competition

02:07.127 --> 02:09.212
specifically designed to test
every aspect

02:09.212 --> 02:11.048
of your bladesmithing
capabilities.

02:11.048 --> 02:13.634
Today's a very special day
for you gentlemen,

02:13.634 --> 02:17.179
because you will be forging
in the 100th competition

02:17.179 --> 02:18.847
here on "Forged in Fire."

02:18.847 --> 02:19.931
<i>♪ ♪</i>

02:19.931 --> 02:20.974
<i>‐ This is the 100th episode.</i>

02:20.974 --> 02:21.975
They could reduce the time

02:21.975 --> 02:22.976
to 100 minutes.

02:22.976 --> 02:24.019
They can make it so where

02:24.019 --> 02:25.020
you only can swing

02:25.020 --> 02:25.979
your hammer 100 times.

02:25.979 --> 02:27.731
<i>I have no idea.</i>

02:27.731 --> 02:29.900
<i>I know it's gonna be hard,</i>
<i>though.</i>

02:29.900 --> 02:31.318
‐ And in honor of this event,

02:31.318 --> 02:33.695
we've collected a piece,
or in some cases,

02:33.695 --> 02:36.365
pieces of steel,
from every single one

02:36.365 --> 02:40.452
of the 99 previous competitions
for you to use.

02:40.452 --> 02:43.080
‐ With all these materials,
I can't even begin to imagine

02:43.080 --> 02:44.873
what the challenge
is going to be.

02:44.873 --> 02:46.750
<i>This is definitely</i>
<i>going to be stressful</i>

02:46.750 --> 02:48.960
and a real test of ability.

02:48.960 --> 02:50.337
‐ You want a boat anchor?
There it is.

02:50.337 --> 02:52.005
You want some armor?
We got it.

02:52.005 --> 02:54.466
You want some gun barrels
to make a knife out of?

02:54.466 --> 02:55.717
Have at it.

02:55.717 --> 02:56.843
You want some springs?

02:56.843 --> 02:58.011
Plenty.

02:58.011 --> 03:00.222
You wanna use
the intake manifold

03:00.222 --> 03:01.848
from a Chevy to make a knife?

03:01.848 --> 03:04.226
Awesome, but it better be
a badass chopper

03:04.226 --> 03:05.852
that's between
12 and 15 inches.

03:05.852 --> 03:08.271
Gentlemen, we expect
to see perfection

03:08.271 --> 03:09.481
when you come in here.

03:09.481 --> 03:11.024
I hope that you practiced.

03:11.024 --> 03:12.901
I hope you watched
the 99 previous episodes,

03:12.901 --> 03:16.738
because your job is to select
at least two of these steels

03:16.738 --> 03:18.699
to forge a competition chopper,

03:18.699 --> 03:20.784
all in front of a panel
of expert judges,

03:20.784 --> 03:22.244
who determine which of you
will be our next

03:22.244 --> 03:23.829
"Forged in Fire" Champion,

03:23.829 --> 03:27.207
walking with a stack of 100
$100 bills.

03:27.207 --> 03:29.042
That's $10,000, gentlemen.

03:29.042 --> 03:30.127
<i>♪ ♪</i>

03:30.127 --> 03:31.461
Let's meet them now.

03:31.461 --> 03:33.422
Up first, two‐time
"Forged in Fire" Champion,

03:33.422 --> 03:34.965
Ben Abbott.

03:34.965 --> 03:36.758
Next, historic weapons
re‐creation specialist,

03:36.758 --> 03:37.968
David Baker.

03:37.968 --> 03:40.053
Last, edged weapon specialist,

03:40.053 --> 03:41.430
Doug Marcaida.

03:41.430 --> 03:43.723
In the second round,
you'll be attaching handles

03:43.723 --> 03:45.976
to those blades, turning them
into fully functional

03:45.976 --> 03:47.352
competition choppers.

03:47.352 --> 03:50.063
They will be tested
for strength and durability

03:50.063 --> 03:52.107
<i>in an ice block chop,</i>

03:52.107 --> 03:55.527
and for edge retention
in a rope slice.

03:55.527 --> 03:56.987
Bladesmiths,
you have three hours

03:56.987 --> 03:58.738
to forge your blades,

03:58.738 --> 04:00.240
and when the time runs out
and the judges have looked

04:00.240 --> 04:02.367
at your work,
they'll select one of you

04:02.367 --> 04:05.078
to surrender your blade
and leave The Forge.

04:05.078 --> 04:06.455
Good luck, bladesmiths.

04:06.455 --> 04:09.082
Your three hours starts...
now.

04:09.082 --> 04:11.918
<i>‐ The 100th round one.</i>

04:11.918 --> 04:13.378
[laughs]

04:13.378 --> 04:15.088
I‐‐I don't even know
how to react to that.

04:15.088 --> 04:17.174
<i>I didn't really expect</i>
<i>99 different types</i>

04:17.174 --> 04:19.885
<i>of material sitting out here</i>
<i>on the table.</i>

04:19.885 --> 04:22.471
<i>I see on the table</i>
<i>there's a stack of 15N20,</i>

04:22.471 --> 04:24.014
<i>and there's a stack of 1095,</i>

04:24.014 --> 04:25.807
<i>and they're already</i>
<i>cut to size,</i>

04:25.807 --> 04:27.225
<i>and I know that I can easily</i>
<i>make a Damascus billet</i>

04:27.225 --> 04:28.894
<i>out of those two stacks.</i>

04:28.894 --> 04:30.562
I'm gonna work that, make sure
the welds are nice and tight,

04:30.562 --> 04:32.272
<i>and then I'm gonna get out</i>
<i>and I'm gonna start</i>

04:32.272 --> 04:33.815
<i>drawing the material out.</i>

04:33.815 --> 04:36.109
‐ There's a lot
of salvaged material out there,

04:36.109 --> 04:38.945
and in 99 competitions
before this...

04:38.945 --> 04:40.405
<i>[exciting music]</i>

04:40.405 --> 04:43.784
<i>We used everything</i>
<i>from golf clubs to armor.</i>

04:43.784 --> 04:45.327
<i>We've used bicycles...</i>

04:45.327 --> 04:46.578
<i>♪ ♪</i>

04:46.578 --> 04:47.954
<i>Horseshoes,</i>

04:47.954 --> 04:48.997
<i>barbed wire.</i>

04:48.997 --> 04:50.290
<i>We used that cannon once.</i>

04:50.290 --> 04:51.416
<i>I think we used</i>
<i>lawn mowers</i>

04:51.416 --> 04:52.834
<i>and a car.</i>

04:52.834 --> 04:53.794
<i>‐ [laughs]</i>

04:53.794 --> 04:55.295
<i>‐ I actually had no idea</i>

04:55.295 --> 04:57.422
<i>this was gonna be</i>
<i>the 100th competition.</i>

04:57.422 --> 04:59.424
So I'm pretty stoked.

04:59.424 --> 05:02.010
I'm used to working
with recycled materials.

05:02.010 --> 05:03.428
<i>I grabbed a lot of steel.</i>

05:03.428 --> 05:06.097
I wanted to make sure
I had a big enough billet.

05:06.097 --> 05:11.144
‐ Is it wise to grab
that recycled material

05:11.144 --> 05:13.271
when there's
so much clean steel over there?

05:13.271 --> 05:15.148
‐ No, I‐‐I'd grab clean.

05:15.148 --> 05:16.316
Clean that I knew.

05:16.316 --> 05:18.443
Nice.
‐ Ben's going for multiple

05:18.443 --> 05:19.528
pieces of steel here.

05:19.528 --> 05:21.863
‐ I also take the angle iron.

05:21.863 --> 05:23.198
<i>♪ ♪</i>

05:23.198 --> 05:25.158
<i>‐ So I've got</i>
<i>four types of steel:</i>

05:25.158 --> 05:27.285
<i>the farrier's rasp, 1095,</i>
<i>leaf spring,</i>

05:27.285 --> 05:29.287
and I chose some files
for good measure,

05:29.287 --> 05:32.457
<i>and I'm turning it into</i>
<i>a large pattern‐welded billet.</i>

05:32.457 --> 05:34.000
‐ Oh, look at that mess.

05:34.000 --> 05:35.836
Well, you can see
all that gapping in there.

05:35.836 --> 05:38.296
He's gonna have to heat it up
in the forge to flatten it out.

05:38.296 --> 05:39.965
‐ Aw, these tongs suck!

05:39.965 --> 05:42.092
‐ But he's gonna be building up
that forge scale

05:42.092 --> 05:44.386
in between those welds
while he's doing it.

05:44.386 --> 05:46.221
‐ I'm a little bit concerned
with the bends

05:46.221 --> 05:49.015
in the leaf springs,
but it should go,

05:49.015 --> 05:50.517
and it should straighten out
as I weld it.

05:50.517 --> 05:52.519
‐ I noticed that Cullen
came over,

05:52.519 --> 05:54.396
and he grabbed some Wite‐Out
from over here.

05:54.396 --> 05:56.022
What's he gonna do with that,
Dave?

05:56.022 --> 05:57.649
‐ He's gonna wreck
his chances of winning.

05:57.649 --> 05:59.317
[laughter]

05:59.317 --> 06:01.444
<i>‐ I am going to try</i>
<i>a canister Damascus today</i>

06:01.444 --> 06:02.654
<i>for the first time ever,</i>

06:02.654 --> 06:03.989
with the ball bearings

06:03.989 --> 06:06.366
<i>and chain and powdered steel.</i>

06:06.366 --> 06:08.285
So I'm going to take steel
I know

06:08.285 --> 06:11.204
and use a process that
I don't know to combine them

06:11.204 --> 06:12.539
and then see what happens.

06:12.539 --> 06:14.708
‐ There are two ways
to make a canister.

06:14.708 --> 06:17.168
One is to line the inside
with the Wite‐Out.

06:17.168 --> 06:19.629
That way, the inside canister
material does not

06:19.629 --> 06:21.214
weld to the canister itself.

06:21.214 --> 06:23.216
But then you have to remove
that canister.

06:23.216 --> 06:25.635
If anything goes wrong,
it takes forever.

06:25.635 --> 06:27.554
Leave the Wite‐Out out,
forge it all together,

06:27.554 --> 06:29.598
grind the can off later.

06:29.598 --> 06:32.267
‐ I would say that Cullen did
the most complicated process

06:32.267 --> 06:34.477
just because
he opted for a canister,

06:34.477 --> 06:36.313
<i>whereas everyone else</i>
<i>just kind of layered</i>

06:36.313 --> 06:37.564
<i>their billets up.</i>

06:37.564 --> 06:39.149
‐ I'm putting more pressure
on myself

06:39.149 --> 06:41.318
<i>than I think</i>
<i>the competition is.</i>

06:41.318 --> 06:44.321
<i>Go big or go home.</i>

06:44.321 --> 06:45.363
[buzzing]

06:45.363 --> 06:46.489
<i>‐ My strategy is</i>

06:46.489 --> 06:47.741
<i>the "KISS" method:</i>

06:47.741 --> 06:49.492
keep it simple, stupid.

06:49.492 --> 06:53.121
<i>I want to try to do the</i>
<i>simplest Damascus you can do,</i>

06:53.121 --> 06:54.456
and that's flat bar.

06:54.456 --> 06:57.334
Um, I chose 15N20
and 1095 and bar stock.

06:57.334 --> 06:58.960
[rattling]

06:58.960 --> 07:03.089
<i>Normally 15N20</i>
<i>and 1095 weld the easiest.</i>

07:03.089 --> 07:05.467
<i>I had to clean all</i>
<i>the flats on the steel,</i>

07:05.467 --> 07:07.135
'cause if you don't,
it won't weld,

07:07.135 --> 07:09.095
so that's what's putting me
behind just a little bit.

07:09.095 --> 07:10.096
<i>♪ ♪</i>

07:10.096 --> 07:11.514
<i>‐ All over my anvil,</i>

07:11.514 --> 07:13.016
<i>I've been writing</i>
<i>with a soapstone.</i>

07:13.016 --> 07:14.351
I have measurements
on this side.

07:14.351 --> 07:15.685
I have sections that
I'm not allowed

07:15.685 --> 07:17.354
to go past on this side.

07:17.354 --> 07:19.314
You know, I have length
of my blade over here,

07:19.314 --> 07:21.524
and then right here
on the back side, I've written,

07:21.524 --> 07:23.151
"Find a third way."

07:23.151 --> 07:25.111
<i>It means when you're backed</i>
<i>into a corner,</i>

07:25.111 --> 07:26.988
<i>you know, try to find another</i>
<i>way to solve the problem.</i>

07:26.988 --> 07:28.948
So, I go over to big blue
with my billet,

07:28.948 --> 07:30.992
<i>and I'm really excited</i>
<i>to set my weld,</i>

07:30.992 --> 07:34.496
<i>and I give it a good solid hit</i>
<i>on my billet and...</i>

07:34.496 --> 07:35.622
<i>♪ ♪</i>

07:35.622 --> 07:37.082
The back end of it
splits apart.

07:37.082 --> 07:38.124
<i>[dramatic music[</i>

07:38.124 --> 07:39.542
<i>So I'm obviously worried,</i>

07:39.542 --> 07:41.544
<i>but I immediately realize</i>
<i>that my billet</i>

07:41.544 --> 07:43.421
<i>is just a little bit too cold.</i>

07:43.421 --> 07:46.132
<i>So, before it cools down</i>
<i>and before that starts to set,</i>

07:46.132 --> 07:47.384
<i>put some more flux on it</i>

07:47.384 --> 07:49.302
<i>and throw it back</i>
<i>into my forge,</i>

07:49.302 --> 07:50.637
<i>so I can get it up</i>
<i>to a better temperature.</i>

07:50.637 --> 07:53.431
I can always find a way
to fix the problem.

07:53.431 --> 07:56.309
<i>[rock music]</i>

07:56.309 --> 07:57.977
<i>♪ ♪</i>

07:57.977 --> 08:00.438
‐ Cullen needs to cut
that canister off.

08:00.438 --> 08:03.274
He's gonna smash that canister
down really tight.

08:03.274 --> 08:05.235
‐ It makes it harder to peel.

08:05.235 --> 08:07.237
‐ Often virtually impossible
to peel.

08:07.237 --> 08:08.321
‐ Oof.

08:08.321 --> 08:10.115
‐ I am starting
to feel frustration

08:10.115 --> 08:11.324
build up in my brain.

08:11.324 --> 08:13.368
This canister
should be coming off.

08:13.368 --> 08:14.577
[bleep]

08:14.577 --> 08:16.246
‐ I think we may see
Cullen struggle

08:16.246 --> 08:18.164
to get enough material
to finish his knife.

08:18.164 --> 08:20.041
<i>‐ If I can't get this can off,</i>

08:20.041 --> 08:23.545
<i>I may have to abandon</i>
<i>this technique and start over.</i>

08:23.545 --> 08:28.591
<i>♪ ♪</i>

08:28.591 --> 08:30.927
‐ Bladesmiths, one hour
has elapsed.

08:30.927 --> 08:33.430
You have two hours remaining
to finish your work.

08:33.430 --> 08:35.515
<i>‐ If I can't get this can off,</i>

08:35.515 --> 08:37.517
<i>I will have wasted</i>
<i>an hour of time</i>

08:37.517 --> 08:39.519
<i>and have nothing to show</i>
<i>for it.</i>

08:39.519 --> 08:40.895
‐ There's a high possibility

08:40.895 --> 08:42.605
that things
are gonna go awry....

08:42.605 --> 08:44.858
‐ That's just it‐‐
‐ When you use that canister.

08:44.858 --> 08:46.526
‐ You're playing the odds.

08:46.526 --> 08:48.403
‐ Instead of wasting time,

08:48.403 --> 08:52.991
I am going to go ahead
and forge down my canister.

08:52.991 --> 08:54.492
‐ You're gonna grind it off?

08:54.492 --> 08:56.202
‐ Uh, it's solid.
I'm just gonna grind it off.

08:56.202 --> 08:57.495
‐ Yeah.
Yeah.

08:57.495 --> 08:58.955
‐ It's not an ideal way
to do it,

08:58.955 --> 09:01.249
<i>because I may still have</i>
<i>some of the mild steel</i>

09:01.249 --> 09:02.792
<i>on my blade,</i>
<i>but it's better</i>

09:02.792 --> 09:04.335
<i>than wasting time</i>

09:04.335 --> 09:06.504
<i>with something</i>
<i>that's not working.</i>

09:06.504 --> 09:08.256
<i>[rock music]</i>

09:08.256 --> 09:09.424
‐ Whew.
I know I got

09:09.424 --> 09:10.884
a good, solid billet.

09:10.884 --> 09:12.510
<i>Just gotta make sure we</i>
<i>get it hot, get it hard,</i>

09:12.510 --> 09:14.262
and let's get this thing
shaped up.

09:14.262 --> 09:15.972
<i>I keep drawing it out</i>
<i>and drawing it out,</i>

09:15.972 --> 09:17.766
<i>and every time I put it</i>
<i>in the forge,</i>

09:17.766 --> 09:20.393
<i>I can see that it's growing,</i>
<i>growing, growing.</i>

09:20.393 --> 09:22.604
I was very concerned
that my stack

09:22.604 --> 09:23.980
<i>wasn't gonna be enough,</i>

09:23.980 --> 09:26.232
<i>but I think I got</i>
<i>too much material.</i>

09:26.232 --> 09:29.360
‐ The length of the face
of the anvil‐‐that's 17 inches.

09:29.360 --> 09:32.238
Mickey's piece is way longer
than that.

09:32.238 --> 09:33.907
So, he could cut off
five inches

09:33.907 --> 09:36.493
and still have plenty
to work with.

09:36.493 --> 09:39.412
<i>‐ Sam's got that‐‐that</i>
<i>leaf spring</i>

09:39.412 --> 09:40.997
he's grinding up right now.

09:40.997 --> 09:43.917
Who knows how abused
that piece of steel has been?

09:43.917 --> 09:45.877
It's a broken leaf spring.

09:45.877 --> 09:47.545
We know it's broken once.

09:47.545 --> 09:49.422
‐ This grinding is taking
a lot less time

09:49.422 --> 09:51.758
than I thought it would,
but I noticed a crack

09:51.758 --> 09:53.927
<i>starting to form on the spine</i>
<i>of my blade.</i>

09:53.927 --> 09:55.720
There was a little bit
of, uh, laminate

09:55.720 --> 09:57.347
that didn't really weld,

09:57.347 --> 09:59.766
<i>but I ground it out</i>
<i>to see if I could get</i>

09:59.766 --> 10:01.935
<i>all the part that wasn't</i>
<i>laminated off,</i>

10:01.935 --> 10:02.936
<i>and I think I did,</i>

10:02.936 --> 10:04.687
so I'm pretty stoked.

10:04.687 --> 10:07.649
‐ I kind of miss the days when
somebody would get on the table

10:07.649 --> 10:10.902
and straddle the grinder.
‐ [laughing]

10:10.902 --> 10:12.570
Oh, God.
I remember that.

10:12.570 --> 10:14.447
We're like, "No, no, no!"

10:14.447 --> 10:16.741
<i>[intense music]</i>

10:16.741 --> 10:19.786
‐ Standing on a box
with a sharp knife.

10:22.831 --> 10:24.791
<i>‐ I wanna heat‐treat,</i>
<i>obviously,</i>

10:24.791 --> 10:25.959
<i>before the time runs out,</i>

10:25.959 --> 10:27.627
so I'm gonna take it over,

10:27.627 --> 10:29.003
and I'm gonna do the quench

10:29.003 --> 10:30.588
and make sure there's no warp.

10:30.588 --> 10:31.673
<i>♪ ♪</i>

10:31.673 --> 10:32.966
‐ Robert just quenched.

10:32.966 --> 10:35.343
This is the part
of the competition

10:35.343 --> 10:39.472
where we have seen things
go horribly wrong.

10:39.472 --> 10:40.974
<i>This is when cracks happen,</i>

10:40.974 --> 10:42.517
when warps appear.
‐ Yeah.

10:42.517 --> 10:43.560
<i>♪ ♪</i>

10:43.560 --> 10:44.644
‐ Don't do it.
‐ Ugh.

10:44.644 --> 10:45.979
‐ Ugh.

10:45.979 --> 10:47.355
<i>♪ ♪</i>

10:47.355 --> 10:48.648
<i>‐ Oh!</i>

10:48.648 --> 10:50.316
‐ I think John's just lost
his blade

10:50.316 --> 10:51.693
in the bottom of the oil.

10:51.693 --> 10:53.486
<i>‐ It looks like it's fine,</i>

10:53.486 --> 10:56.072
<i>but as I skate my file</i>
<i>across it,</i>

10:56.072 --> 10:58.867
I realize my file isn't
skating at all.

10:58.867 --> 11:00.493
It's starting to dig.

11:00.493 --> 11:03.746
<i>I am feeling</i>
<i>just absolutely defeated,</i>

11:03.746 --> 11:06.583
but I have to find a third way.

11:06.583 --> 11:07.750
‐ Going again?

11:07.750 --> 11:09.502
‐ The more times
that you quench a blade,

11:09.502 --> 11:11.337
the more stress that you put on
that material.

11:11.337 --> 11:13.840
As much as I don't wanna quench
my blade a second time,

11:13.840 --> 11:16.509
I'm gonna have to if I wanna
stay in.

11:16.509 --> 11:19.387
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

11:19.387 --> 11:21.681
Pull it out.
Moment of truth...

11:21.681 --> 11:24.392
<i>♪ ♪</i>

11:24.392 --> 11:25.518
And it's a success!

11:25.518 --> 11:26.686
<i>My knife is hard.</i>

11:26.686 --> 11:28.354
<i>♪ ♪</i>

11:28.354 --> 11:31.024
<i>‐ Quenching, I feel,</i>
<i>is the most important part</i>

11:31.024 --> 11:32.901
<i>in the blade making process.</i>

11:32.901 --> 11:34.360
<i>♪ ♪</i>

11:34.360 --> 11:36.738
This is when the blade
is actually given life.

11:36.738 --> 11:38.531
<i>♪ ♪</i>

11:38.531 --> 11:39.699
[scraping]

11:39.699 --> 11:41.075
<i>File skates across the edge,</i>

11:41.075 --> 11:43.494
so I know I have successfully
hardened the blade.

11:43.494 --> 11:46.581
<i>♪ ♪</i>

11:46.581 --> 11:49.042
<i>And then I see that there</i>
<i>is a slight warp in the blade.</i>

11:49.042 --> 11:51.002
<i>I think this warp</i>
<i>is manageable.</i>

11:51.002 --> 11:53.046
<i>I think I can take it out</i>
<i>in the next round,</i>

11:53.046 --> 11:56.925
so I am not going to risk
doing a second quench.

11:56.925 --> 11:58.051
<i>♪ ♪</i>

11:58.051 --> 11:59.385
<i>‐ My blade's really hot.</i>

11:59.385 --> 12:00.637
<i>It's time to quench.</i>

12:00.637 --> 12:01.846
‐ Sam's just heating up his oil

12:01.846 --> 12:03.389
with a piece of angle iron.

12:03.389 --> 12:04.724
‐ Yeah, I really wish that Sam

12:04.724 --> 12:06.059
would leave that
in the oil longer.

12:06.059 --> 12:07.560
It's so screaming hot.

12:07.560 --> 12:08.937
‐ Leave it in there.

12:08.937 --> 12:10.897
‐ Whoa, watch your face.

12:10.897 --> 12:12.941
‐ Don't need to shave anymore.

12:12.941 --> 12:15.902
‐ Well, here in The Forge
it seems to be fireball!

12:15.902 --> 12:17.403
Fireball! Fireball!

12:17.403 --> 12:18.738
<i>♪ ♪</i>

12:18.738 --> 12:21.908
Aaron, please don't catch
your face on fire.

12:21.908 --> 12:23.785
<i>♪ ♪</i>

12:23.785 --> 12:25.078
<i>all: Oh!</i>

12:25.078 --> 12:28.081
<i>♪ ♪</i>

12:28.081 --> 12:29.916
‐ 15 minutes, bladesmiths.

12:29.916 --> 12:31.459
‐ Right now,
I'm just trying to get

12:31.459 --> 12:33.086
a good profile
on the blade.

12:33.086 --> 12:34.921
‐ I'm getting a little bit
worried about Mickey.

12:34.921 --> 12:37.090
I mean, it's great.
He's doing a lot of shaping,

12:37.090 --> 12:38.091
but it's time.

12:38.091 --> 12:39.175
‐ And now would be the time

12:39.175 --> 12:40.802
for Mickey to get in
that quench.

12:40.802 --> 12:42.136
‐ Exactly.

12:42.136 --> 12:43.721
<i>‐ Right now,</i>
<i>I'm cutting it close.</i>

12:43.721 --> 12:44.931
I need to get the quench done.

12:44.931 --> 12:46.432
<i>That there is gonna either</i>

12:46.432 --> 12:47.976
<i>make me or break me.</i>

12:47.976 --> 12:50.103
We'll find out if we got
a blade or not.

12:50.103 --> 12:51.813
<i>[suspenseful music]</i>

12:51.813 --> 12:53.606
‐ Mickey's quenched.

12:53.606 --> 12:56.442
Five, four, three,

12:56.442 --> 12:58.152
two, one.

12:58.152 --> 13:00.071
Bladesmiths, shut down
your machines.

13:00.071 --> 13:01.656
Drop your tools.

13:01.656 --> 13:06.119
This first round in our
100th competition is over.

13:06.119 --> 13:07.870
[cheers and applause]

13:07.870 --> 13:09.706
<i>‐ To all the smiths</i>
<i>that have competed</i>

13:09.706 --> 13:12.959
<i>in the 99 competitions</i>
<i>before me,</i>

13:12.959 --> 13:14.877
<i>my hat goes off to y'all,</i>

13:14.877 --> 13:16.879
because this was tough.

13:18.464 --> 13:19.507
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

13:19.507 --> 13:21.134
‐ Bladesmiths, the first round

13:21.134 --> 13:23.511
in our 100th competition
is over.

13:23.511 --> 13:26.014
Now it's time to see
what you've done.

13:26.014 --> 13:29.142
Mickey, please present
your blade to the judges.

13:29.142 --> 13:31.519
<i>♪ ♪</i>

13:31.519 --> 13:32.979
<i>‐ Okay, Mickey, I make swords.</i>

13:32.979 --> 13:35.148
Most of them don't weigh
this much.

13:35.148 --> 13:36.774
You got a lot of material
here, man.

13:36.774 --> 13:38.943
Having said that,
the steel's beautiful,

13:38.943 --> 13:40.737
the shape's good,

13:40.737 --> 13:42.864
but there's a lot of refinement
to do on this

13:42.864 --> 13:46.200
before it's gonna be
a comfortable knife to wield.

13:46.993 --> 13:48.494
‐ All right, Cullen.
You're up.

13:48.494 --> 13:49.871
<i>♪ ♪</i>

13:49.871 --> 13:53.249
‐ You must have put some
big ball bearings in here,

13:53.249 --> 13:55.626
because that's pretty ballsy
to go with something‐‐

13:55.626 --> 13:58.171
in a competition‐‐that you've
never done before.

13:58.171 --> 13:59.672
Way to challenge yourself.

13:59.672 --> 14:02.508
There is a warp
on your blade here,

14:02.508 --> 14:04.510
but overall, I like the shape.
Good job.

14:04.510 --> 14:05.720
<i>♪ ♪</i>

14:05.720 --> 14:06.929
‐ Robert, you're up.

14:06.929 --> 14:08.514
Please present your blade
to the judges.

14:08.514 --> 14:10.516
<i>♪ ♪</i>

14:10.516 --> 14:13.061
<i>‐ Well, Robert, your welds</i>
<i>are nice and tight.</i>

14:13.061 --> 14:15.271
I don't see any evidence
of delamination.

14:15.271 --> 14:17.023
You edge kind of meanders.

14:17.023 --> 14:19.901
I'd like to see a flatter grind
on that edge.

14:19.901 --> 14:21.527
The overall shape I like.

14:21.527 --> 14:24.614
The one thing I'm not a super
fan of is the handle.

14:24.614 --> 14:26.199
It'd be interesting to see
if you can

14:26.199 --> 14:29.035
make this more
of a human‐sized hand.

14:29.035 --> 14:31.746
‐ All right, Robert.
The handle that you have‐‐

14:31.746 --> 14:34.540
the size‐‐it's built for
a man's hand.

14:34.540 --> 14:35.750
<i>♪ ♪</i>

14:35.750 --> 14:37.710
[laughter]

14:37.710 --> 14:39.170
<i>[rock music]</i>

14:39.170 --> 14:42.048
‐ I will turn this table around
and take it home.

14:42.965 --> 14:44.175
‐ All right, Sam.

14:44.175 --> 14:46.219
Please present your blade
to the judges.

14:46.219 --> 14:48.054
<i>♪ ♪</i>

14:48.054 --> 14:51.224
<i>‐ When you stacked up</i>
<i>your billet to weld it,</i>

14:51.224 --> 14:53.226
the leaf spring was still
like that.

14:53.226 --> 14:54.852
There was a giant gap in there,

14:54.852 --> 14:58.147
and I have a feeling
that's that seam

14:58.147 --> 15:00.066
<i>that we're seeing.</i>

15:00.066 --> 15:02.819
There are cold shuts that
are running through this blade.

15:02.819 --> 15:05.238
A lot of this is just
gonna need to be thinned out,

15:05.238 --> 15:08.866
and I'm worried that if you
get down to the center,

15:08.866 --> 15:12.245
you're gonna start digging
into these and open them up.

15:12.245 --> 15:13.704
<i>♪ ♪</i>

15:13.704 --> 15:15.873
‐ The judges' deliberation
is complete.

15:15.873 --> 15:17.834
They've made
their final decision.

15:17.834 --> 15:20.837
It's time
for our round one dismissal

15:20.837 --> 15:22.338
of one of you bladesmiths.

15:22.338 --> 15:25.091
The bladesmith leaving
The Forge is...

15:25.091 --> 15:27.885
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

15:27.885 --> 15:29.095
Sam.

15:29.095 --> 15:30.763
Your blade didn't make the cut.

15:30.763 --> 15:32.265
David Baker's gonna
tell you why.

15:32.265 --> 15:35.309
‐ Sam, the multiple
cold shuts, seams,

15:35.309 --> 15:38.729
that we can see in your blade,
we don't feel can be fixed.

15:38.729 --> 15:41.065
Uh, that and your blade
is by far the least finished.

15:41.065 --> 15:42.733
That's why we're letting
you go.

15:42.733 --> 15:43.943
<i>♪ ♪</i>

15:43.943 --> 15:45.778
‐ Sam, please surrender
your blade.

15:45.778 --> 15:47.280
<i>♪ ♪</i>

15:47.280 --> 15:49.282
<i>‐ This has been a really</i>
<i>exciting opportunity</i>

15:49.282 --> 15:51.284
<i>to be on</i>
<i>the 100th competition,</i>

15:51.284 --> 15:54.287
but I didn't get
my one real goal

15:54.287 --> 15:55.955
of just getting past
the first round.

15:55.955 --> 15:58.040
<i>I wish the other competitors</i>
<i>good luck.</i>

15:58.040 --> 15:59.792
<i>They're a great group of guys.</i>

15:59.792 --> 16:02.086
They all are deserving
of moving on.

16:02.086 --> 16:04.380
<i>♪ ♪</i>

16:04.380 --> 16:06.632
‐ Bladesmiths, congratulations.

16:06.632 --> 16:08.759
Your work has landed you
in the second round

16:08.759 --> 16:11.429
of this 100th competition
here in The Forge,

16:11.429 --> 16:13.014
and now that your blades
have been tempered,

16:13.014 --> 16:14.807
it's time to turn them
into fully functional

16:14.807 --> 16:17.727
competition choppers
by attaching handles to them.

16:17.727 --> 16:19.854
Because this is
the 100th challenge

16:19.854 --> 16:21.898
in this forge,
we're not just gonna ask

16:21.898 --> 16:23.691
for one extra feature
on your blades.

16:23.691 --> 16:25.818
Instead, we wanna see
all the features.

16:25.818 --> 16:27.320
<i>♪ ♪</i>

16:27.320 --> 16:29.780
<i>We wanna see a liner</i>
<i>on the handle of your blade.</i>

16:29.780 --> 16:31.365
<i>We wanna see a mosaic pin.</i>

16:31.365 --> 16:33.242
<i>We wanna see you use</i>
<i>at least two different</i>

16:33.242 --> 16:35.161
<i>handle materials</i>
<i>on your handles.</i>

16:35.161 --> 16:36.329
Keep in mind that after

16:36.329 --> 16:37.371
the time runs out
in this round,

16:37.371 --> 16:38.789
your weapons will be tested

16:38.789 --> 16:39.999
for strength and durability

16:39.999 --> 16:42.043
in an ice block chop,

16:42.043 --> 16:44.879
and for edge‐retention
in a bladesmith favorite,

16:44.879 --> 16:46.297
rope chop.

16:46.297 --> 16:48.174
Gentlemen, good luck.

16:48.174 --> 16:50.426
Your three hours starts now.

16:50.426 --> 16:52.178
<i>[exciting music]</i>

16:52.178 --> 16:54.931
Doug, talk to me a little bit
about strategy in this round.

16:54.931 --> 16:57.683
‐ They have to think about
putting an edge on your blade

16:57.683 --> 17:00.853
that can survive the ice chop

17:00.853 --> 17:02.772
and at the same time,
cut through that rope.

17:02.772 --> 17:06.025
‐ The main thing I have to do
is I have to reheat the blade.

17:06.025 --> 17:08.778
The only way to remove
that warp is to get it warm.

17:08.778 --> 17:09.862
<i>[rock music]</i>

17:09.862 --> 17:11.697
And I have to re‐harden it.

17:11.697 --> 17:14.867
I will not move forward
if I have this warp.

17:14.867 --> 17:17.036
‐ Cullen is in a spot
of trouble.

17:17.036 --> 17:19.247
He's removed the hardness
from his blade,

17:19.247 --> 17:23.417
and we could have
something catastrophic go down

17:23.417 --> 17:24.877
in our strength test.

17:24.877 --> 17:26.879
<i>♪ ♪</i>

17:26.879 --> 17:28.756
<i>[exciting music]</i>

17:28.756 --> 17:30.883
‐ Three hours is gonna be
a tight time crunch

17:30.883 --> 17:32.718
for me to get
all this work done,

17:32.718 --> 17:35.388
but if God's willing
and the creek don't rise,

17:35.388 --> 17:36.389
I'll have it done.

17:36.389 --> 17:37.473
<i>♪ ♪</i>

17:37.473 --> 17:39.058
‐ Mickey's got so much material

17:39.058 --> 17:40.935
to lose on that blade
that he's gonna have

17:40.935 --> 17:43.729
to come up with a way
to grind deep and fast

17:43.729 --> 17:45.064
to lighten that thing up.

17:45.064 --> 17:47.233
‐ I grind better not hearing
the grinder

17:47.233 --> 17:48.859
or hearing anything else
around me,

17:48.859 --> 17:52.154
<i>so I'ma get</i>
<i>my earmuffs on,</i>

17:52.154 --> 17:54.824
<i>head on over to the grinders,</i>
<i>and I'ma get in the zone.</i>

17:54.824 --> 17:57.410
<i>[tranquil music]</i>

17:57.410 --> 18:00.204
<i>At times, it ain't nothing</i>
<i>but me</i>

18:00.204 --> 18:03.249
and the task that
is in front of me.

18:03.249 --> 18:05.751
<i>♪ ♪</i>

18:05.751 --> 18:07.086
<i>[rock music]</i>

18:07.086 --> 18:08.921
<i>‐ The first thing</i>
<i>I'm going to do is make</i>

18:08.921 --> 18:10.256
<i>my mosaic pin,</i>

18:10.256 --> 18:11.757
and then my game plan
for the handle is to take

18:11.757 --> 18:15.011
two pieces of Micarta
with a liner in between,

18:15.011 --> 18:16.470
so you get a nice
color contrast.

18:16.470 --> 18:19.849
And I'm starting to realize
that my Micarta

18:19.849 --> 18:22.935
<i>is not even thickness.</i>

18:22.935 --> 18:24.145
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

18:24.145 --> 18:26.772
<i>My big concern is the shape</i>

18:26.772 --> 18:28.274
<i>and comfortability</i>
<i>of my handle.</i>

18:28.274 --> 18:29.900
It's certainly not
gonna be comfortable against

18:29.900 --> 18:32.069
the really intense shocks
that are coming of hitting

18:32.069 --> 18:33.446
something like an ice block.

18:33.446 --> 18:36.824
I need to scrap it and try
to find a better solution.

18:36.824 --> 18:38.826
<i>This is not good.</i>

18:38.826 --> 18:40.995
[sighs]

18:40.995 --> 18:42.455
<i>[rock music]</i>

18:42.455 --> 18:44.832
‐ So, the time wasted in trying
to get the blade

18:44.832 --> 18:47.376
re‐heat treated‐‐that's
time coming off the clock,

18:47.376 --> 18:50.880
and I'm pretty sure we don't
have access

18:50.880 --> 18:52.173
to the oil in the second round.

18:52.173 --> 18:54.467
I'm gonna have to quench it
in water.

18:54.467 --> 18:55.968
‐ Man.
‐ Oh, no.

18:55.968 --> 18:57.470
Don't put that in water
when you're done.

18:57.470 --> 19:00.348
‐ Can't a blade that has been
quenched in water

19:00.348 --> 19:02.308
snap in the quench?

19:02.308 --> 19:03.976
‐ Oh, it can‐‐it can explode

19:03.976 --> 19:05.186
in the water.
‐ Can it shatter in the quench?

19:05.186 --> 19:06.395
‐ Oh, yeah.
‐ Yeah.

19:06.395 --> 19:07.813
‐ Oh, into the water.

19:07.813 --> 19:09.148
Into the water.
‐ Water quenching.

19:09.148 --> 19:10.483
‐ Did he...?
‐ Ooh‐hoo‐hoo.

19:10.483 --> 19:12.526
‐ What the...
‐ Did you see‐‐did you

19:12.526 --> 19:13.611
just see what happened?

19:13.611 --> 19:15.112
‐ I'm not believing this.

19:15.112 --> 19:17.365
<i>[rock music]</i>

19:17.365 --> 19:18.491
‐ [bleep]

19:18.491 --> 19:23.162
<i>♪ ♪</i>

19:23.162 --> 19:25.414
‐ Lo and behold,
some more of the warp

19:25.414 --> 19:27.083
actually came out of my blade.
It actually

19:27.083 --> 19:29.168
<i>bent back</i>
<i>in the other direction.</i>

19:29.168 --> 19:32.338
‐ Well, gentlemen, we can have
a very "fra‐gee‐lay" blade

19:32.338 --> 19:34.173
going into our strength test.

19:34.173 --> 19:37.927
‐ I'm in total elation
right now that this worked.

19:39.011 --> 19:40.346
<i>[exciting music]</i>

19:40.346 --> 19:43.057
‐ Mickey has done a great job
turning that blade

19:43.057 --> 19:45.142
into a real competition knife
here.

19:45.142 --> 19:46.602
<i>♪ ♪</i>

19:46.602 --> 19:48.562
<i>‐ I'm having</i>
<i>a hard time drilling.</i>

19:48.562 --> 19:50.106
<i>I'm having to go slow,</i>

19:50.106 --> 19:52.108
<i>and I'm hearing</i>
<i>screaming and screaming.</i>

19:52.108 --> 19:53.401
<i>That ain't a good thing.</i>

19:53.401 --> 19:54.402
<i>[bleep]</i>

19:54.402 --> 19:55.528
I got a delam.

19:55.528 --> 19:57.154
<i>♪ ♪</i>

19:57.154 --> 20:00.032
<i>My drill bit was actually</i>
<i>pushing the delam apart.</i>

20:00.032 --> 20:01.409
[whistles]

20:01.409 --> 20:03.411
I wanna say a few choice words.

20:03.411 --> 20:05.037
Damn it, boy.

20:05.037 --> 20:09.291
‐ Bladesmiths, you have
just 60 fleeting minutes

20:09.291 --> 20:10.960
to finish your work.

20:10.960 --> 20:13.379
<i>‐ Right now I don't have time</i>
<i>to cut it off.</i>

20:13.379 --> 20:14.880
I'm just gonna fill it
with epoxy

20:14.880 --> 20:16.382
and put it in between
the knife scales.

20:16.382 --> 20:18.259
<i>Hopefully, it don't come back</i>
<i>to get me.</i>

20:18.259 --> 20:21.303
<i>♪ ♪</i>

20:21.303 --> 20:23.180
<i>‐ Since my initial plan</i>
<i>didn't work,</i>

20:23.180 --> 20:26.225
my solution is to make
four layers of handle material.

20:26.225 --> 20:27.643
<i>♪ ♪</i>

20:27.643 --> 20:29.437
‐ Any time you need to hammer
a pin in like that,

20:29.437 --> 20:30.688
you've kind of got a problem.

20:30.688 --> 20:32.148
‐ Yeah.

20:32.148 --> 20:34.275
<i>‐ As I'm trying</i>
<i>to push it through,</i>

20:34.275 --> 20:36.193
<i>it's just peeling apart.</i>

20:36.193 --> 20:38.529
And it pushes layers apart
in such a way that

20:38.529 --> 20:41.282
the wood is splintering
and it's breaking.

20:41.282 --> 20:44.243
This is not pretty and it's
definitely not going to work.

20:44.243 --> 20:45.578
<i>I have to find a third way.</i>

20:45.578 --> 20:47.288
<i>♪ ♪</i>

20:47.288 --> 20:49.039
‐ Everything I'm trying to do
in round two

20:49.039 --> 20:50.624
is taking longer
than it needs to,

20:50.624 --> 20:52.918
<i>and I am running out of time.</i>

20:52.918 --> 20:55.254
I gotta get the holes drilled
in the scales.

20:56.505 --> 21:00.176
<i>[suspenseful music]</i>

21:00.176 --> 21:01.635
‐ Oh!
‐ Oh.

21:01.635 --> 21:03.262
‐ Oh!
<i>‐ I have watched</i>

21:03.262 --> 21:06.307
<i>all 99 previous episodes</i>
<i>of "Forged in Fire,"</i>

21:06.307 --> 21:08.768
and, uh, I never thought
it would be this difficult.

21:08.768 --> 21:11.771
‐ Gentlemen, you only have
15 minutes remaining

21:11.771 --> 21:12.813
in this round.

21:12.813 --> 21:14.607
<i>‐ I am sharpening my blade,</i>

21:14.607 --> 21:16.317
polishing my blade,
putting my handle on.

21:16.317 --> 21:17.485
Essentially, I am doing

21:17.485 --> 21:19.069
the entire
second round challenge

21:19.069 --> 21:20.863
<i>in the last minutes</i>
<i>of the challenge.</i>

21:20.863 --> 21:24.241
I am 90% sure I am not
finishing this blade.

21:24.241 --> 21:27.286
<i>♪ ♪</i>

21:27.286 --> 21:28.621
<i>‐ I got a handle.</i>

21:28.621 --> 21:31.332
It's on and it's got pins.

21:31.332 --> 21:33.626
<i>So, being I only got</i>
<i>10 minutes left,</i>

21:33.626 --> 21:36.128
I need to go over and hock
as much material and liner

21:36.128 --> 21:37.671
<i>off this handle as possible.</i>

21:37.671 --> 21:39.340
<i>And I hope I don't have</i>
<i>a delam</i>

21:39.340 --> 21:40.800
<i>somewhere in the center</i>
<i>that could blow apart</i>

21:40.800 --> 21:42.635
<i>on the ice chop.</i>

21:42.635 --> 21:43.636
<i>♪ ♪</i>

21:43.636 --> 21:45.346
<i>‐ Here we are, third try,</i>

21:45.346 --> 21:46.639
and I got to put my pins
through,

21:46.639 --> 21:49.600
and I've drilled my holes
in the wrong place...

21:50.392 --> 21:51.477
[bleep]

21:51.477 --> 21:53.646
<i>And I'm starting over again.</i>

21:53.646 --> 21:54.855
‐ Five minutes.

21:54.855 --> 21:56.315
‐ [laughs]

21:56.315 --> 21:57.650
‐ What would you do if you
were Robert right now?

21:57.650 --> 21:59.276
‐ I mean, with five minutes
left...

21:59.276 --> 22:00.694
<i>♪ ♪</i>

22:00.694 --> 22:01.654
I got nothing.

22:01.654 --> 22:02.905
‐ We're ticking down.

22:02.905 --> 22:04.573
Robert doesn't have
a handle on.

22:04.573 --> 22:06.325
Cullen doesn't have
a handle on.

22:06.325 --> 22:09.245
As with our previous
99 episodes,

22:09.245 --> 22:13.290
you just never know what's
gonna happen here in The Forge.

22:13.290 --> 22:15.167
‐ Ow.

22:15.167 --> 22:16.293
God.

22:16.293 --> 22:17.545
[snapping]

22:17.545 --> 22:19.338
‐ Ray's put in another order
for coffee.

22:19.338 --> 22:20.673
[laughter]

22:20.673 --> 22:22.508
‐ If the block is here,
I can flick,

22:22.508 --> 22:25.511
and I can capture and tuck
and puncture with the karambit.

22:25.511 --> 22:27.680
‐ Man, do that to me.
I like that.

22:27.680 --> 22:29.223
‐ I decide to take horn.

22:29.223 --> 22:32.810
Taking a liner, I slide
my tiny, tiny mosaic pin

22:32.810 --> 22:36.522
into my opening and wrap
my blade in paracord.

22:36.522 --> 22:40.150
‐ Hey, the five minute handle
to get in, go ahead.

22:40.150 --> 22:41.819
Do what you gotta do
to qualify.

22:41.819 --> 22:43.863
<i>‐ If this doesn't work,</i>

22:43.863 --> 22:45.698
I'm not moving on.

22:45.698 --> 22:48.784
‐ Five, four, three,

22:48.784 --> 22:50.703
two, one.

22:50.703 --> 22:52.413
Bladesmiths, shut down
your machines.

22:52.413 --> 22:53.956
Drop your tools.

22:53.956 --> 22:55.958
This competition is over.

22:55.958 --> 22:58.544
‐ Things did not go my way
this round,

22:58.544 --> 23:02.381
and now, I am hoping that
my blade will make it

23:02.381 --> 23:04.466
through testing, and I can
make it into round three

23:04.466 --> 23:06.343
<i>in spite of all of that.</i>

23:06.343 --> 23:09.346
‐ All right, gentlemen, it's
time for the strength test:

23:09.346 --> 23:10.681
the ice block chop.

23:10.681 --> 23:12.391
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

23:12.391 --> 23:14.393
This test is all about what
that ice does to your knife,

23:14.393 --> 23:16.645
not what your knife
does to that ice.

23:16.645 --> 23:18.772
Mickey, you're up first.
You ready?

23:18.772 --> 23:20.399
‐ Yes, sir.

23:20.399 --> 23:21.483
<i>♪ ♪</i>

23:21.483 --> 23:22.568
<i>This is gonna be the test</i>

23:22.568 --> 23:23.861
<i>I'm most worried about.</i>

23:23.861 --> 23:26.780
<i>I could have a cold shut</i>
<i>or a, uh, delam</i>

23:26.780 --> 23:29.533
<i>in the blade, like I did</i>
<i>at the very end.</i>

23:29.533 --> 23:31.368
If there's a delam,
it's gonna blow it apart.

23:31.368 --> 23:34.413
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

23:34.413 --> 23:38.667
<i>♪ ♪</i>

23:38.667 --> 23:39.919
[thud]

23:39.919 --> 23:42.922
[cracking]

23:42.922 --> 23:47.635
<i>♪ ♪</i>

23:47.635 --> 23:49.386
[thud]

23:49.386 --> 23:52.765
<i>♪ ♪</i>

23:55.517 --> 23:56.602
‐ Phew.

23:56.602 --> 23:57.853
‐ First up, Mickey,

23:57.853 --> 24:00.230
there's not a mark
on that edge,

24:00.230 --> 24:03.275
and the shape of this handle
locks my hand in.

24:03.275 --> 24:04.526
Well done.

24:04.526 --> 24:05.569
‐ Thank you, sir.

24:05.569 --> 24:06.779
‐ All right, Cullen.
You ready?

24:06.779 --> 24:08.572
‐ I'm ready.
‐ Okay.

24:08.572 --> 24:09.949
<i>♪ ♪</i>

24:09.949 --> 24:11.992
<i>‐ My handle is not held</i>
<i>together very well.</i>

24:11.992 --> 24:16.288
I'm pretty sure my handle
is gonna blow apart.

24:16.288 --> 24:19.833
<i>♪ ♪</i>

24:19.833 --> 24:22.836
[cracking]

24:22.836 --> 24:25.798
<i>[rock music]</i>

24:25.798 --> 24:32.972
<i>♪ ♪</i>

24:33.806 --> 24:34.807
[thud]

24:34.807 --> 24:37.685
<i>♪ ♪</i>

24:39.311 --> 24:41.689
[thudding]

24:41.689 --> 24:43.315
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

24:43.315 --> 24:44.650
‐ All right, Cullen.

24:44.650 --> 24:46.527
Good news is your blade's
in one piece.

24:46.527 --> 24:48.821
It's got a little bit
of rolling

24:48.821 --> 24:50.364
right along this edge here.

24:50.364 --> 24:52.574
Bad news is, there are parts
coming off your handle.

24:52.574 --> 24:53.742
It's a problem.

24:53.742 --> 24:56.495
<i>♪ ♪</i>

24:56.495 --> 24:57.871
When I was swinging this,
it literally

24:57.871 --> 24:59.915
was chewing on my hand,

24:59.915 --> 25:02.292
but it's not
a catastrophic failure.

25:02.292 --> 25:03.585
Can I still hold it?
Yes.

25:03.585 --> 25:05.879
Would I choose to hold it?
Uh, probably not.

25:05.879 --> 25:07.715
[laughs]

25:07.715 --> 25:09.466
Robert, your turn.

25:09.466 --> 25:10.592
We good?

25:10.592 --> 25:11.593
‐ As I'll ever be.

25:11.593 --> 25:12.594
‐ [laughs]
Okay.

25:12.594 --> 25:19.727
<i>♪ ♪</i>

25:20.728 --> 25:23.689
<i>[rock music]</i>

25:23.689 --> 25:26.734
[cracking]

25:26.734 --> 25:27.860
[thud]

25:27.860 --> 25:34.950
<i>♪ ♪</i>

25:38.495 --> 25:39.872
[thudding]

25:40.831 --> 25:42.708
<i>[intense music]</i>

25:42.708 --> 25:43.751
‐ All right, Robert.

25:43.751 --> 25:46.045
Your wrap here is so bumpy

25:46.045 --> 25:48.505
that it's nothing
but hot spots.

25:48.505 --> 25:49.757
<i>♪ ♪</i>

25:49.757 --> 25:51.508
That's not our real issue,
though.

25:51.508 --> 25:55.763
Our real issue are where
this metal blew out on a delam.

25:55.763 --> 25:58.599
So basically, this entire
section of the blade

25:58.599 --> 26:01.477
has those delams chipping away.

26:01.477 --> 26:05.481
<i>♪ ♪</i>

26:05.481 --> 26:08.525
‐ All right, bladesmiths,
this is the sharpness test.

26:08.525 --> 26:10.527
Now in our first competition,

26:10.527 --> 26:11.737
we did a rope slice.

26:11.737 --> 26:14.823
<i>♪ ♪</i>

26:14.823 --> 26:16.992
<i>Well today,</i>
<i>on our 100th competition,</i>

26:16.992 --> 26:18.619
we're gonna do it again.

26:18.619 --> 26:19.745
Wil.

26:19.745 --> 26:22.664
<i>[suspenseful music]</i>

26:22.664 --> 26:23.957
<i>♪ ♪</i>

26:23.957 --> 26:26.043
This is our version
of a birthday candle.

26:26.043 --> 26:27.753
Mickey, you're up first.
You ready for this?

26:27.753 --> 26:33.217
‐ Yes, sir.
‐ Make a wish.

26:33.217 --> 26:35.886
<i>[suspenseful music</i>
<i>crescendos]</i>

26:35.886 --> 26:37.471
[slash]

26:39.932 --> 26:41.517
‐ [whistles]

26:42.184 --> 26:44.937
Oh‐ho‐ho.
[laughs]

26:44.937 --> 26:48.232
‐ Your edge‐‐one and done.

26:48.232 --> 26:49.149
Good job, sir.

26:49.149 --> 26:51.902
Your blade‐‐it will cut.

26:51.902 --> 26:53.403
‐ Thank you, sir.

26:53.403 --> 26:54.613
‐ All right, Cullen.
It's your turn.

26:54.613 --> 26:56.281
You ready?
‐ I'm ready.

26:56.281 --> 26:57.491
‐ Let's do this.

26:57.491 --> 27:00.452
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

27:00.452 --> 27:07.459
<i>♪ ♪</i>

27:07.459 --> 27:10.546
<i>[music crescendos]</i>

27:14.091 --> 27:16.093
‐ [laughs]

27:16.093 --> 27:17.219
‐ First, your handle.

27:17.219 --> 27:18.595
Another piece
just came off.

27:18.595 --> 27:21.014
It did also dig into the hand,

27:21.014 --> 27:25.936
But your blade is sharp
to cut through in two strikes.

27:25.936 --> 27:27.604
It will cut.
‐ Thank you.

27:27.604 --> 27:29.231
‐ All right, Robert.
It's your turn.

27:29.231 --> 27:30.190
You ready for this?

27:30.190 --> 27:31.483
‐ Definitely.

27:31.483 --> 27:33.193
I have edge damage,

27:33.193 --> 27:37.364
so I'm really concerned
moving into the sharpness test.

27:37.364 --> 27:41.285
<i>♪ ♪</i>

27:41.285 --> 27:42.494
[whispered] Ah, damn.

27:42.494 --> 27:44.246
<i>♪ ♪</i>

27:44.246 --> 27:47.291
<i>[music crescendos]</i>

27:47.291 --> 27:50.586
<i>♪ ♪</i>

27:56.091 --> 27:58.260
‐ Your edge is sharp enough

27:58.260 --> 28:00.178
to cut through two layers
of the rope,

28:00.178 --> 28:03.515
but overall, you have
a very stout blade right here.

28:03.515 --> 28:04.933
It's like an axe head.

28:04.933 --> 28:07.144
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

28:07.144 --> 28:10.147
‐ Bladesmiths, the judges
have passed

28:10.147 --> 28:12.149
their final decision.

28:12.149 --> 28:13.984
The bladesmith leaving
The Forge is...

28:13.984 --> 28:17.404
<i>♪ ♪</i>

28:17.404 --> 28:18.405
Robert.

28:18.405 --> 28:19.698
Your blade didn't make the cut.

28:19.698 --> 28:21.366
Ben Abbott's gonna tell
you why.

28:21.366 --> 28:22.993
‐ Robert, in the strength test,

28:22.993 --> 28:25.245
bits of your edge blew off
at the weld seams.

28:25.245 --> 28:28.165
Also, your obtuse geometry
and damaged edge

28:28.165 --> 28:30.334
caused a failure
in the sharpness test,

28:30.334 --> 28:32.210
and it's for those reasons
that we're sending you home.

28:32.210 --> 28:33.420
<i>♪ ♪</i>

28:33.420 --> 28:35.297
‐ Robert, please surrender
your blade.

28:35.297 --> 28:36.548
<i>♪ ♪</i>

28:36.548 --> 28:38.258
<i>‐ I gave it everything</i>
<i>that I had,</i>

28:38.258 --> 28:39.551
<i>so I guess</i>

28:39.551 --> 28:41.553
<i>you can't really</i>
<i>ask more than that.</i>

28:41.553 --> 28:44.348
Bladesmithing is really
important to me.

28:44.348 --> 28:45.599
[laughs]

28:45.599 --> 28:47.434
<i>Really, quite literally,</i>
<i>bladesmithing</i>

28:47.434 --> 28:50.187
<i>saved my life and I wanted</i>
<i>to win to show</i>

28:50.187 --> 28:52.439
<i>other vets that are</i>
<i>struggling like I am</i>

28:52.439 --> 28:55.192
<i>that there's something</i>
<i>else that's out there.</i>

28:55.192 --> 28:57.694
[laughs]
There's always a third way.

28:57.694 --> 29:00.405
<i>♪ ♪</i>

29:01.281 --> 29:03.742
‐ Mickey, Cullen,
congratulations.

29:03.742 --> 29:06.495
You fellas have made it
into the final round.

29:06.495 --> 29:09.081
Well, now we're sending
you back your home forge

29:09.081 --> 29:13.085
to recreate a very specific
and iconic weapon from history.

29:13.085 --> 29:14.419
Are you ready to see
what it is?

29:14.419 --> 29:15.587
All right.

29:15.587 --> 29:17.130
That weapon is...

29:17.130 --> 29:20.217
[dramatic music]

29:20.759 --> 29:22.219
The o‐katana.

29:22.219 --> 29:23.762
<i>♪ ♪</i>

29:23.762 --> 29:25.722
<i>Translating roughly to</i>
<i>"big sword,"</i>

29:25.722 --> 29:28.225
<i>the o‐katana</i>
<i>is a classic Japanese blade</i>

29:28.225 --> 29:30.435
<i>longer than</i>
<i>the typical katana,</i>

29:30.435 --> 29:33.230
<i>and is also referred</i>
<i>to as a "daito."</i>

29:33.230 --> 29:35.315
<i>One of Japan's</i>
<i>most iconic swords,</i>

29:35.315 --> 29:37.109
<i>the familiar katana</i>
<i>is synonymous</i>

29:37.109 --> 29:39.319
<i>with the bushido lifestyle</i>
<i>of Japan's samurai,</i>

29:39.319 --> 29:41.363
<i>and while the shorter katana's</i>
<i>single‐edged blade</i>

29:41.363 --> 29:44.616
<i>was sharp enough to sever</i>
<i>a head in a single stroke,</i>

29:44.616 --> 29:48.036
<i>the o‐katana's longer blade</i>
<i>allowed for greater reach</i>

29:48.036 --> 29:49.496
<i>and a more powerful cut.</i>

29:49.496 --> 29:51.540
<i>Although samurai culture</i>
<i>was effectively barred</i>

29:51.540 --> 29:53.458
<i>near the end</i>
<i>of the 19th century,</i>

29:53.458 --> 29:55.335
<i>the katana remains a symbol</i>
<i>of the warrior</i>

29:55.335 --> 29:56.795
<i>and immaculate bladesmithing.</i>

29:56.795 --> 29:58.630
The length of your blade

29:58.630 --> 30:01.675
must be between 31
and 33 inches.

30:01.675 --> 30:03.760
You must include
a <i>habaki</i> that is between

30:03.760 --> 30:05.512
one and two inches in length.

30:05.512 --> 30:07.389
You must have
a <i>tsuba</i> ‐style guard

30:07.389 --> 30:09.558
and a traditional
wrapped handle.

30:09.558 --> 30:11.059
‐ [exhales sharply]

30:11.059 --> 30:12.436
‐ You have five days
at your home forges

30:12.436 --> 30:14.479
in which to complete
these blades,

30:14.479 --> 30:17.482
and when you come back,
the judges will announce

30:17.482 --> 30:19.484
which of you is
the "Forged in Fire" Champion,

30:19.484 --> 30:21.653
only after they've tested
the hell out of them

30:21.653 --> 30:23.363
and inspected your work.

30:23.363 --> 30:24.614
Good luck, bladesmiths.

30:24.614 --> 30:26.199
We'll see you in five days.

30:26.199 --> 30:27.534
<i>♪ ♪</i>

30:27.534 --> 30:30.370
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

30:30.370 --> 30:32.664
<i>‐ It's day one,</i>
<i>and I'm getting ready to start</i>

30:32.664 --> 30:34.416
<i>on the o‐katana.</i>

30:34.416 --> 30:35.834
<i>♪ ♪</i>

30:35.834 --> 30:38.170
<i>This is gonna be</i>
<i>the first blade I've ever made</i>

30:38.170 --> 30:39.546
<i>that's this size,</i>

30:39.546 --> 30:40.672
<i>so the first thing</i>
<i>I'm gonna do</i>

30:40.672 --> 30:43.258
<i>is hammer out a practice blade</i>

30:43.258 --> 30:45.385
out of mild steel

30:45.385 --> 30:48.180
<i>to figure out what techniques</i>
<i>I need to use</i>

30:48.180 --> 30:50.557
<i>to actually forge</i>
<i>the real blade.</i>

30:50.557 --> 30:52.184
<i>♪ ♪</i>

30:52.184 --> 30:53.685
<i>Discover just by beveling it,</i>

30:53.685 --> 30:55.854
<i>I can get the curve</i>
<i>in the blade that I need.</i>

30:55.854 --> 30:57.481
That's probably the biggest
thing I'm taking away

30:57.481 --> 30:59.691
from forging this practice one.

30:59.691 --> 31:04.196
<i>♪ ♪</i>

31:04.196 --> 31:05.530
<i>‐ Being back home,</i>

31:05.530 --> 31:07.449
I'm cooking cornbread
in my own house,

31:07.449 --> 31:09.367
and I know where
the cornmeal's at.

31:09.367 --> 31:11.703
<i>♪ ♪</i>

31:11.703 --> 31:14.539
<i>I think the hardest part</i>
<i>about this o‐katana</i>

31:14.539 --> 31:16.875
is just the sheer length
of it.

31:16.875 --> 31:18.335
It's gonna take a little time

31:18.335 --> 31:20.170
for this big bar of steel
to heat up.

31:20.170 --> 31:21.505
<i>♪ ♪</i>

31:21.505 --> 31:23.340
Heat, beat, repeat.

31:23.340 --> 31:25.342
<i>Being out here in the heat‐‐</i>

31:25.342 --> 31:27.219
<i>you know, it's almost</i>
<i>100 and something degrees‐‐</i>

31:27.219 --> 31:29.429
<i>it‐‐it's taking it out of me.</i>

31:29.429 --> 31:32.599
<i>I'm happy with it,</i>
<i>but right now I'm just tired.</i>

31:32.599 --> 31:33.892
<i>♪ ♪</i>

31:33.892 --> 31:35.644
<i>‐ So it's the start</i>
<i>of day two.</i>

31:35.644 --> 31:37.813
<i>That practice blade</i>
<i>let me work out some kinks</i>

31:37.813 --> 31:41.358
<i>that I think I'm gonna need</i>
<i>to make the real blade.</i>

31:41.358 --> 31:42.734
<i>Well, the main goal today</i>

31:42.734 --> 31:44.694
<i>is to get the blade</i>
<i>all forged out</i>

31:44.694 --> 31:47.531
<i>and hopefully heat‐treated</i>
<i>by tonight.</i>

31:47.531 --> 31:49.241
<i>By waiting to start the blade,</i>

31:49.241 --> 31:51.243
<i>that definitely doesn't</i>
<i>leave me a lot of time</i>

31:51.243 --> 31:52.744
<i>in case something goes wrong.</i>

31:52.744 --> 31:54.246
<i>Fatigue is setting in.</i>

31:54.246 --> 31:56.164
<i>My hammer's falling</i>
<i>out of my hands.</i>

31:56.164 --> 31:57.582
As of right now,
whatever I'm doing

31:57.582 --> 31:59.501
is probably just
making it worse.

31:59.501 --> 32:01.753
Can't do any more tonight.

32:01.753 --> 32:02.671
<i>♪ ♪</i>

32:02.671 --> 32:03.880
<i>‐ It's day three.</i>

32:03.880 --> 32:05.841
<i>Get Ugly Betty cranked up,</i>

32:05.841 --> 32:09.386
<i>and then we'll start trying to</i>
<i>get this thing heat‐treated.</i>

32:09.386 --> 32:11.179
Ooh, doggie.

32:11.179 --> 32:13.598
This thing's so long
and so hard to make

32:13.598 --> 32:15.684
that it'd be hard
to restart back over,

32:15.684 --> 32:17.435
so it's all or nothing today.

32:17.435 --> 32:18.979
<i>[tense music]</i>

32:18.979 --> 32:21.773
<i>This blade is so long</i>
<i>that anything can happen,</i>

32:21.773 --> 32:24.401
so I'm worried about it
a little bit.

32:24.401 --> 32:31.241
<i>♪ ♪</i>

32:31.241 --> 32:33.618
Here's the moment of truth.

32:33.618 --> 32:36.663
My file's able to eat some
of the metal off of it.

32:36.663 --> 32:38.498
It ain't skatin'
the way it's supposed to.

32:38.498 --> 32:40.667
This blade did not harden.

32:40.667 --> 32:41.626
<i>♪ ♪</i>

32:41.626 --> 32:43.420
Put it back in the forge,

32:43.420 --> 32:44.713
and, uh, let's try this again.

32:44.713 --> 32:46.673
Come on, Ugly Betty,
do me good today.

32:46.673 --> 32:48.300
Do me good.

32:48.300 --> 32:49.676
<i>I'm a little nervous right now</i>

32:49.676 --> 32:51.678
<i>because there could be</i>
<i>a stress fracture</i>

32:51.678 --> 32:54.514
<i>in there somewhere, just from</i>
<i>heating and cooling,</i>

32:54.514 --> 32:55.724
<i>heating and cooling.</i>

32:55.724 --> 33:00.645
I need this really bad
right now.

33:00.645 --> 33:02.314
‐ No guts, no glory!
No guts, n

33:02.314 --> 33:05.650
<i>I need this quench</i>
<i>to be a charm.</i>

33:05.650 --> 33:12.324
<i>♪ ♪</i>

33:12.324 --> 33:14.117
Hot damn!
That [bleep] worked.

33:14.117 --> 33:15.285
Whoo!

33:15.285 --> 33:20.665
I may...
have an o‐katana now, boys!

33:20.665 --> 33:22.042
Ha‐ha!

33:22.042 --> 33:23.001
Whoo!

33:23.001 --> 33:25.003
<i>♪ ♪</i>

33:25.003 --> 33:26.171
<i>‐ It's the start of day five.</i>

33:26.171 --> 33:27.881
<i>Blade has been tempered.</i>

33:27.881 --> 33:29.382
<i>I have to get the edge put on,</i>

33:29.382 --> 33:32.344
and then I just need to finish
constructing the handle.

33:32.344 --> 33:33.678
<i>♪ ♪</i>

33:33.678 --> 33:36.223
Slow, but it's getting there.

33:36.223 --> 33:38.183
<i>I left it</i>
<i>a little bit concave,</i>

33:38.183 --> 33:40.185
<i>just because I don't know</i>
<i>what tests they're gonna do,</i>

33:40.185 --> 33:42.020
<i>and it may not cut as well,</i>

33:42.020 --> 33:43.980
<i>because it doesn't have</i>
<i>an edge for slicing,</i>

33:43.980 --> 33:46.066
<i>but I think it'll still</i>
<i>do some damage.</i>

33:46.066 --> 33:47.692
<i>It's not the prettiest blade,</i>

33:47.692 --> 33:49.361
<i>but it meets all the</i>
<i>parameters they gave us</i>

33:49.361 --> 33:51.029
<i>for an o‐katana, so</i>

33:51.029 --> 33:53.156
at least it'll be testable.

33:53.156 --> 33:55.700
<i>Take ugly‐but‐functional</i>
<i>any day.</i>

33:55.700 --> 33:58.703
<i>[tranquil woodwind music]</i>

33:58.703 --> 33:59.913
<i>♪ ♪</i>

33:59.913 --> 34:02.207
‐ I just want to hear Doug say,

34:02.207 --> 34:04.334
"It will kill."

34:04.334 --> 34:05.710
Feeling good.

34:05.710 --> 34:06.920
Time to get started.

34:06.920 --> 34:09.798
I'm ready to dress up
the o‐katana.

34:09.798 --> 34:11.466
Tap, tap, tap.

34:11.466 --> 34:14.719
<i>Hopefully today, we'll have</i>
<i>all the parts fitted up to it.</i>

34:14.719 --> 34:16.137
<i>♪ ♪</i>

34:16.137 --> 34:18.139
<i>I'm trying to fit the</i> habaki
<i>to the blade,</i>

34:18.139 --> 34:20.350
<i>and I noticed a crack.</i>

34:20.350 --> 34:22.727
Damn it, boy.

34:22.727 --> 34:25.480
<i>So now I'ma have to go back</i>
<i>and re‐braze the</i> habaki.

34:25.480 --> 34:27.107
<i>♪ ♪</i>

34:27.107 --> 34:28.358
<i>Now it's too tight,</i>

34:28.358 --> 34:29.734
so I might have to go
to filing.

34:29.734 --> 34:33.405
<i>♪ ♪</i>

34:33.405 --> 34:35.156
The status update right now is,

34:35.156 --> 34:36.700
the <i>habaki's</i> fitted on.

34:36.700 --> 34:38.159
We're gonna, uh,

34:38.159 --> 34:39.828
put a little silver solder
on it,

34:39.828 --> 34:41.746
and then we'll also put
the guard on,

34:41.746 --> 34:44.124
and then start working
on the handle.

34:44.124 --> 34:46.042
<i>Right now, the only thing</i>
<i>I'm really worried about</i>

34:46.042 --> 34:48.753
<i>is maybe there might be</i>
<i>a little stress on the blade.</i>

34:48.753 --> 34:49.879
<i>♪ ♪</i>

34:49.879 --> 34:51.256
Well, let's see what we got.

34:51.256 --> 34:56.261
<i>♪ ♪</i>

34:56.261 --> 34:57.804
That's it!

34:57.804 --> 34:58.847
We're gonna glue her up,

34:58.847 --> 35:00.098
just like it is.

35:00.098 --> 35:03.476
<i>♪ ♪</i>

35:03.476 --> 35:05.020
<i>I just pulled up.</i>
<i>I see</i>

35:05.020 --> 35:06.354
<i>that we're at a gun range,</i>

35:06.354 --> 35:08.106
and the only thing
that my mind goes back to

35:08.106 --> 35:09.524
is episode number one,

35:09.524 --> 35:11.985
<i>where they shoot the blade</i>
<i>with the bullet.</i>

35:11.985 --> 35:14.487
[slow‐motion gunshot]

35:14.487 --> 35:16.948
‐ Mickey, Cullen, welcome back,

35:16.948 --> 35:18.283
and welcome to the gun range.

35:18.283 --> 35:19.868
Mickey, how'd it go for you?

35:19.868 --> 35:21.036
‐ Everything went good.

35:21.036 --> 35:22.287
<i>♪ ♪</i>

35:22.287 --> 35:25.540
<i>I made my o‐katana</i>
<i>out of 1075.</i>

35:25.540 --> 35:28.001
<i>I used copper</i>
<i>for all the fittings.</i>

35:28.001 --> 35:30.962
<i>And used a rattlesnake inlay</i>
<i>for the handle.</i>

35:30.962 --> 35:33.340
‐ Nice.
Cullen, how'd you do?

35:33.340 --> 35:35.300
‐ It was definitely
a challenge.

35:35.300 --> 35:36.801
<i>♪ ♪</i>

35:36.801 --> 35:39.804
<i>I also made my blade</i>
<i>out of 1075.</i>

35:39.804 --> 35:41.473
<i>Mild steel</i>
<i>for all the fittings.</i>

35:41.473 --> 35:43.433
<i>I'm hoping that it either</i>
<i>does really well,</i>

35:43.433 --> 35:45.810
<i>or just explodes on screen.</i>

35:45.810 --> 35:47.270
‐ [laughs]

35:47.270 --> 35:48.938
All right, gentlemen,
well, your weapons

35:48.938 --> 35:50.982
will now be put through
a series of three tests.

35:50.982 --> 35:53.318
Up first, the strength test.
Dave?

35:53.318 --> 35:54.861
<i>♪ ♪</i>

35:54.861 --> 35:56.988
‐ All right, gentlemen,
it's time for the bullet split.

35:56.988 --> 35:58.490
Now, if you pass this test,

35:58.490 --> 36:01.159
you get to, uh,
join a very elite club:

36:01.159 --> 36:03.119
<i>our bulletproof sword club.</i>

36:03.119 --> 36:04.954
[gunshot]
‐ Yes!

36:04.954 --> 36:06.998
‐ Split it.
‐ [laughing]

36:06.998 --> 36:08.333
‐ Look at that.
‐ Damn.

36:08.333 --> 36:09.334
‐ Whoo!
‐ I think

36:09.334 --> 36:10.418
that did it.
‐ Yep.

36:10.418 --> 36:11.878
‐ Now, to handle this test,

36:11.878 --> 36:14.172
we've got our own 15‐year
military veteran

36:14.172 --> 36:17.050
and deadly weapon, Wil Willis.
Wil?

36:17.050 --> 36:19.219
<i>‐ I've never shot a blade</i>
<i>before,</i>

36:19.219 --> 36:20.804
and why would I?

36:20.804 --> 36:22.472
The only people that I know
that would shoot a blade

36:22.472 --> 36:25.517
<i>is all the judges</i>
<i>on "Forged in Fire."</i>

36:25.517 --> 36:27.227
<i>♪ ♪</i>

36:27.227 --> 36:28.353
[gun clicks]

36:28.353 --> 36:35.443
<i>♪ ♪</i>

36:36.069 --> 36:38.363
[slow‐motion gunshot]

36:40.990 --> 36:42.200
It done it.
‐ Did it hit?

36:42.200 --> 36:43.535
‐ Yeah, it hit it.

36:43.535 --> 36:46.204
‐ First off,
blade's in one piece.

36:46.204 --> 36:47.497
Good job. [chuckles]

36:47.497 --> 36:50.083
Though, you did take
a bit of a deflection.

36:50.083 --> 36:53.002
There are two small rolls on
either side of the deflection,

36:53.002 --> 36:55.171
but you survived.
Welcome to the club.

36:55.171 --> 36:57.006
‐ Thank you, sir.

36:57.006 --> 36:58.883
‐ All right, Cullen, you're up.
Are you ready?

36:58.883 --> 37:00.552
‐ Shoot the [bleep] out of it.

37:00.552 --> 37:05.014
<i>♪ ♪</i>

37:05.014 --> 37:06.141
[gunshot]

37:06.141 --> 37:08.184
<i>♪ ♪</i>

37:08.184 --> 37:09.394
Did it?
‐ Yeah.

37:09.394 --> 37:11.020
It split all over the place.
‐ Okay.

37:11.020 --> 37:12.147
‐ Cullen, you can clearly see

37:12.147 --> 37:13.523
where the bullet
hit the blade‐‐

37:13.523 --> 37:15.275
little bits of bullet
right there‐‐

37:15.275 --> 37:17.610
but there's no deflection
to your edge.

37:17.610 --> 37:19.571
Welcome to the club.
Your blade survived.

37:19.571 --> 37:21.281
‐ Thank you.
‐ All right,

37:21.281 --> 37:22.574
next up is the kill test,

37:22.574 --> 37:24.409
and for that,
I'll give you to Doug.

37:24.409 --> 37:26.244
<i>♪ ♪</i>

37:26.244 --> 37:27.412
‐ All right, bladesmiths,

37:27.412 --> 37:29.122
this is the kill test.

37:29.122 --> 37:31.374
I will take your o‐katana
and deliver killing blows

37:31.374 --> 37:33.042
on this ballistics dummy.

37:33.042 --> 37:34.294
<i>♪ ♪</i>

37:34.294 --> 37:35.628
Mickey, you're up first.
You ready for this?

37:35.628 --> 37:37.547
‐ You know it.
‐ Let's do this.

37:37.547 --> 37:40.258
<i>‐ I've designed my blade</i>
<i>to do one thing:</i>

37:40.258 --> 37:43.344
slice, cut, and kill.

37:43.344 --> 37:49.267
<i>♪ ♪</i>

37:49.267 --> 37:52.353
<i>[heavy rock music]</i>

37:52.353 --> 37:55.064
<i>♪ ♪</i>

37:55.064 --> 37:56.316
‐ [grunts]

37:56.316 --> 38:00.278
‐ [chuckling]

38:00.278 --> 38:03.114
‐ All right, Mickey, let's talk
about your o‐katana right here.

38:03.114 --> 38:05.074
To be able to wield a sword
this size,

38:05.074 --> 38:07.452
the handle is what drives
the blade.

38:07.452 --> 38:09.704
It's hard to get very accurate
because it's big,

38:09.704 --> 38:12.332
but what I love
about your blade

38:12.332 --> 38:15.210
is how sharp your edge is.

38:15.210 --> 38:18.046
It cut into the skull.
Pieces of it came off.

38:18.046 --> 38:20.673
And what's important
about this katana is...

38:20.673 --> 38:22.425
it will kill.
‐ Thank you, sir.

38:26.137 --> 38:27.472
‐ Cullen, it's your turn.
Are you ready for this?

38:27.472 --> 38:28.890
Let's do this.

38:28.890 --> 38:30.809
‐ Knowing how my edge is,

38:30.809 --> 38:34.646
I'm a little worried
that I'm just gonna bounce off.

38:34.646 --> 38:36.064
<i>♪ ♪</i>

38:36.064 --> 38:39.025
<i>[heavy rock music]</i>

38:39.025 --> 38:41.194
<i>♪ ♪</i>

38:41.194 --> 38:44.948
[grunting]

38:44.948 --> 38:46.658
‐ Damn it.

38:46.658 --> 38:48.701
<i>♪ ♪</i>

38:48.701 --> 38:51.663
‐ All right, Cullen, let's talk
about your o‐katana here.

38:51.663 --> 38:54.707
First up, the ginormous handle.

38:54.707 --> 38:58.837
It's very hard to grab
a complete grip on this,

38:58.837 --> 39:01.047
but you have a very sharp tip

39:01.047 --> 39:03.800
that punctures easily
into this ballistics dummy.

39:03.800 --> 39:06.177
But it doesn't lacerate
on the way out.

39:06.177 --> 39:08.054
It did crush the skull,

39:08.054 --> 39:09.514
and any kind of damage
like this

39:09.514 --> 39:11.099
done to anybody...

39:11.099 --> 39:13.518
It will kill.
‐ Thank you.

39:13.518 --> 39:16.062
‐ All right, bladesmiths,
next up, the sharpness test.

39:16.062 --> 39:18.064
The quad sugarcane cuts.

39:18.064 --> 39:19.566
Mickey, you're up first.

39:19.566 --> 39:21.109
You ready for this?
‐ Hell yeah.

39:21.109 --> 39:22.360
‐ [laughs] Let's do this.

39:22.360 --> 39:29.075
<i>♪ ♪</i>

39:29.075 --> 39:32.078
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

39:32.078 --> 39:36.332
<i>♪ ♪</i>

39:36.332 --> 39:38.042
‐ [laughing]

39:38.042 --> 39:44.883
<i>♪ ♪</i>

39:44.883 --> 39:46.009
That was good, man.

39:46.009 --> 39:47.343
‐ That was awesome, man.
‐ That was good.

39:47.343 --> 39:49.554
‐ All right, Mickey,
as you can see,

39:49.554 --> 39:51.806
all the way through
with each swing that I do

39:51.806 --> 39:55.268
with this blade,
the edge is razor sharp.

39:55.268 --> 39:56.936
The balance of this is good.

39:56.936 --> 39:59.731
I can follow through
and still control the blade,

39:59.731 --> 40:03.693
and... it will cut. Good job.
‐ Thank you, sir.

40:03.693 --> 40:05.028
‐ All right, Cullen,
it's your turn, sir.

40:05.028 --> 40:06.738
Are you ready?
‐ Let's do it.

40:06.738 --> 40:08.031
‐ Let's do this.

40:08.031 --> 40:09.741
‐ So going
into the sharpness test,

40:09.741 --> 40:11.743
knowing that I don't have
much of an edge,

40:11.743 --> 40:14.996
<i>it's a hot [bleep] mess.</i>

40:14.996 --> 40:22.086
<i>♪ ♪</i>

40:29.302 --> 40:30.970
‐ It cut.
‐ Mm.

40:30.970 --> 40:32.305
‐ All right, Cullen,

40:32.305 --> 40:34.682
as you can see,
we start with the handle.

40:34.682 --> 40:36.309
Your wrap is starting
to come undone.

40:36.309 --> 40:39.896
Now your edge‐‐
there is no edge on the blade.

40:39.896 --> 40:41.272
The sheer weight alone

40:41.272 --> 40:44.776
and in a very thick,
obtuse blade here‐‐

40:44.776 --> 40:47.987
it more crushes the sugarcanes
than cuts it.

40:47.987 --> 40:50.615
So, you have the honor
of saying,

40:50.615 --> 40:51.658
it will crush.

40:51.658 --> 40:53.201
‐ [chuckles]

40:53.201 --> 40:56.245
‐ Bladesmiths, the judges have
made their final decision.

40:56.245 --> 40:58.873
Only one of you can be our new
"Forged in Fire" Champion,

40:58.873 --> 40:59.958
and that champion is...

40:59.958 --> 41:02.377
<i>♪ ♪</i>

41:02.377 --> 41:03.878
Mickey.
Congratulations,

41:03.878 --> 41:05.713
you're the new "Forged in Fire"
Champion.

41:05.713 --> 41:09.050
Cullen, unfortunately,
your blade didn't make the cut.

41:09.050 --> 41:10.677
Ben Abbot's gonna tell you why.

41:10.677 --> 41:13.012
‐ Well, Cullen, the edge
geometry you put on your sword

41:13.012 --> 41:15.139
just wouldn't cut,
and your handle‐‐

41:15.139 --> 41:16.641
the wrap is just coming apart.

41:16.641 --> 41:18.851
‐ Absolutely.
‐ You put up a good fight,

41:18.851 --> 41:20.937
but at this time,
I have to ask you to please

41:20.937 --> 41:22.939
surrender your o‐katana.

41:22.939 --> 41:24.190
‐ Mickey.
‐ Good job, brother.

41:24.190 --> 41:26.734
‐ Good job.
‐ Good job.

41:26.734 --> 41:28.987
<i>‐ Little disappointed,</i>
<i>but structurally,</i>

41:28.987 --> 41:30.363
<i>Mickey's blade</i>
<i>was just better,</i>

41:30.363 --> 41:32.949
<i>and I agree</i>
<i>with the judges' decision.</i>

41:32.949 --> 41:35.702
Lookin' forward to going home,
but I would not trade

41:35.702 --> 41:36.995
<i>this experience for anything.</i>

41:36.995 --> 41:38.746
<i>It's been great.</i>

41:38.746 --> 41:40.039
I'm the 100th runner up,

41:40.039 --> 41:42.375
so that's not
a bad consolation prize.

41:42.375 --> 41:44.335
<i>♪ ♪</i>

41:44.335 --> 41:46.254
‐ Mickey, congratulations.

41:46.254 --> 41:48.006
You are the new
"Forged in Fire" Champion,

41:48.006 --> 41:50.133
and that is a title
that comes with a check

41:50.133 --> 41:52.260
for $10,000.
Good job, brother.

41:52.260 --> 41:53.845
‐ [chuckles]

41:53.845 --> 41:57.056
Man, I am
the "Forged in Fire" Champion.

41:57.056 --> 41:59.350
<i>I just made a $10,000 sword,</i>

41:59.350 --> 42:02.854
<i>and I'm happier than a tick</i>
<i>in a coon dog's ear, buddy.</i>

42:02.854 --> 42:04.856
[laughs]

42:04.856 --> 42:09.193
<i>♪ ♪</i>
